ssession table per game and deriving `L_t`, `F_t`, `N_t`, `M_t` there.","Both scripts target the same season-level metric and same source data, but the repo provides no single canonical pipeline, so extending or fixing season WMI requires choosing which implementation is the 'new' one."],"suggestion":"Pick one canonical season-processing path and refactor both scripts to share it. The cleaner direction is to extract one reusable per-game possession/WMI builder module, then have both season scripts call that shared API with different season ranges.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"unfinished_wmi_formula_migration"},{"dimension":"incomplete_migration","identifier":"old_step2_parser_coexists_with_direct_raw_action_pipeline","summary":"The older step-based possession parser remains beside newer scripts that bypass it and reimplement possession grouping.","related_files":["step2_build_possessions.py","build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py"],"evidence":["`step2_build_possessions.py:38-125` still defines the step-2 possession parser and outputs `start_time`, `end_time`, `defensive_foul_count`, and `defensive_foul_teams` as if that were the possession-building entry point.","Newer scripts do not import that parser. `build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py:82-150` and `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py:61-100` each rebuild possession grouping directly from raw play-by-play events.","That leaves two coexisting ways to produce possessions in the same codebase, with no wrapper or deprecation note explaining which path is current and which is legacy."],"suggestion":"Either retire `step2_build_possessions.py` into an archive/experiment area, or extract its shared possession-building rules into a common module and make the newer scripts import that module instead of reimplementing the grouping logic.","confidence":"medium","impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"unfinished_wmi_formula_migration"}],"retrospective":{"root_causes":["The WMI formula and possession definitions changed several times in late February, but superseded code paths were kept in place instead of being retired or funneled behind one shared API.","Exploration scripts were promoted into long-lived project files without a cleanup pass to separate current pipeline code from historical experiments."],"likely_symptoms":["stale_checkpoint_logic_keeps_old_wmi_schema","season_wmi_has_two_competing_implementations","old_step2_parser_coexists_with_direct_raw_action_pipeline"],"possible_false_positives":[]}}
